label: The Diary of Charles Drayton I, 1791-1798
description: Includes day-to-day management of Drayton plantations, (particularly Drayton Hall,  Jehossee and Long Savannah), focusing on crops, livestock, labor, and the movement  of these between estates. Charles describes (in brief) meeting and dining with  President George Washington, receiving plant specimens from Thomas Jefferson,  a visit from Andre Michaux, the winding up of Bob Savannah plantation, lease of  plantation on the Wateree River, abuse of slaves, sending slaves from Drayton Hall  to reside at Jehossee, family deaths, division of the deceased's estates and family  acrimony.
